7.body: Paperbit has two distinct parts, the graphics engine and the utilities .
7.title: Core Concepts

8.body: When we create an instance of Paperbit, two classes are initialized. PaperbitCanvas Is the responsible of creating the canvas and the WebGL context. His job is to request frames to the PaperbitAPI, when a frame call is complete it sends to the gpu all the data in a single draw call. PaperbitAPI Is the responsible of creating the frame data and managing events. When the PaperbitCanvas request a frame it will fire the needed events (OnStart, onDraw, onMouseMove ...). Once the onDraw returns, it will send to the PaperbitCanvas all the geometry. This isolation on the canvas and the api let us to create the canvas on the main thread and use the api on a web worker .
8.title: Graphics Engine

9.body: When using a graphics library, it is always nice to have some common features in our disposal: Vector operations Matrix operations Geometric operations Smooth the transition of a number They are not related in any way to the graphics engine, so we could make the same without using them. The purpose of the utilities is to avoid reinventing the wheel in each project.
